  "prompt": "What is the difference between Raw and Smackdown in WWE?",
  "response": "In WWE (World Wrestling Entertainment), Raw and SmackDown are two separate weekly professional wrestling television shows that feature different rosters of wrestlers:\n\n1. Raw:\n- Traditionally aired on Monday nights\n- Red brand/color\n- Generally considered the \"flagship\" show\n- Typically features a larger roster of wrestlers\n- Historically has been the primary WWE show\n\n2. SmackDown:\n- Traditionally aired on Friday nights (currently Fridays on FOX)\n- Blue brand/color\n- Typically has a smaller, more focused roster\n- Often considered the secondary show\n\nBoth shows have their own unique wrestlers, championships, storylines, and events, though wrestlers can sometimes appear on both shows or be traded between brands. They also each have their own pay-per-view events and compete in annual brand competitions like Survivor Series.\n\nThe brand split concept has existed at different times since 2002, with periods of unified and separate rosters. Currently, they are separate brands with distinct identities within WWE.",
